metadata.name: The Face We Had #238
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot

metadata.name: Alpinism #114
metadata.description:
“Only those who will risk going too far can possibly find out how far one can go.” - T.S. Eliot

---

Alpinism is a tribute to the rugged and wild landscapes that rise around us. Which may at once intrigue, impress, intimidate, and inspire.

I am captivated by the mythology of these settings. Where natural shapes appear fantastical. A ridge line drawn by pen meets sky poured out from neon gradient. Where observation is made through the lens of imagination.

Each piece begins with the concept of a mountain landscape. A number of ranges are drawn by pen in one of three styles. Within each style is a spectrum of variation that produces different drawn qualities. The backdrop may be an imagined sky, an impossible sunset, a piece of parchment. A testament to the interpreter’s memory of the scene. 

---
- Made with p5js in the White Mountains of NH July 2022
- press s to save png

metadata.name: A Pocket Full of Wonder #11
metadata.description:
"A Pocket Full of Wonder" invites you to embark on a journey where the boundaries between technology and art are blurred. 

Here, machine-generated images serve as a foundation for a vibrant and dynamic world of code-driven art. This union of artificial intelligence and creative coding evokes a sense of wonder and discovery, as each piece reveals the beauty that can be born from the interplay of technology and art. 

With "A Pocket Full of Wonder", we explore the limitless possibilities that emerge when we allow technology to augment and enhance our artistic visions.

metadata.name: Badgirs City #203
metadata.description:
"I used to live in a small city placed at the center of Iran's plateau with the warmest summer days in the country part; spending most of my childhood with my sweet grandma at her old house. She was always keeping her eyes on me not to get heat stroke at noon playing in the yard when the sun was at its peak glowing furiously. Sundays at noon were my favorite, I used to call them “Ice cream” noons sitting beside the nicest person you could imagine and enjoying a delightful ice cream. You won't know how lovely it was to have an ice cream relaxing under the most enjoyable cold breeze of the tallest windcatcher in the city at her house. "



The Badgirs city is the first collaboration between Fleep and IceRain on Fxhash. The concept was established first with the design of a school with a feeling of safe and nostalgia reminding us of the good memories of our childhood as the grandma’s house and the windcatcher for Fleep.
A windcatcher (Badgir) is an Iranian traditional architectural element in the form of a small tower built on the roof of houses in warm locations to create passive cooling. The collection of Badgirs city is a modern recreational development of those traditional windcatchers designed by Fleep and icerain and exquisitely translated into code by Icerain.

Controls:
[1] Set the resolution to Medium Resolution
[2] Set the resolution to High Resolution

metadata.name: RAUSCH #109
metadata.description:
RAUSCH is a series of generative artworks that explore imaginary digital architectures. 

This series challenges traditional notions of architectural representation and raises important questions about the role of resolution in design. Just as the pixel resolution of an image affects its perceived quality, the resolution of an architectural space can affect its qualities and livability. By embracing digital variation through codes, this series explores the interplay between abstract and concrete space through multiple resolutions. 

RAUSCH is inspired by the feeling of being overwhelmed by complex, chaotic and messy sensations, and aims to engage the viewer through a sense of wonder, disorientation, and awe.

Released on the occasion of Companions of Code, a group exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art at The NFT Gallery in London. 
Curated by Micol Ap. Exhibition 10-24 February 2023 

___________________________________________________

metadata.name: A Gift of Nature #130
metadata.description:
Can nature really be a gift if it isn't ours to give?
Do we feel the need to bind it close in the ways of old to live?
If a gift was given would all be forgiven, a place of harmony now we can live in?

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

A gift of nature, sort of. As natural as a digital gift can be. It is a gen art token of my gratitude you might say. It is the younger sibling of "The Spectrum of Nature". 

This is a gift from me to you, a gift of nature that pulls you through. 

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

To know more about the concept and technicalities of this piece, see the fxtext article “The spectrum of nature - a short making of”. However, feel free to skip the article.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Basic info:
The initial render will be 1000px wide and 1000px high. With the ability to scale this up (see below).

The piece uses WebGL, so will perform much better with a graphics card. A faster computer will obviously be better, though I've done my very best to make it fast and efficient for any old laptop. My hope is that you will find the render process quick and enjoyable for the amount of detail that’s present.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Controls:
Press the [s] key to save the initial render. You will need to wait a few seconds after all the elements have stopped loading. For the [s] key to work you may need to open in a new tab. But can right click save otherwise.

Larger sizes:
Press the [2-9] keys to save a resolution of that key size. So [2] saves a 2000x2000 size image, [9] saves a 9000x9000 size image etc. Unless you are making some very large prints you probably won’t need more than 4k (even 2-3k is big). Though the option is there.

There may be slight variations in the textures for the larger renders, this is because the shader code has to redraw the textures at the higher pixel resolution, and getting the textures where they sit is more of an art than a science. All the elements remain exact however.

/*./*..\*./*..\*../*./*..\*./*..\*.

Made with javascript and some small extra code:
A palette creator by @nathansonic
Noisejs - github.com/josephg/noisejs - Perlin noise generator
Twgl - github.com/greggman/twgl.js - A small webGL helper.

metadata.name: Constellations #24
metadata.description:
We look at things that are seemingly random and can't help but form relationships between them. For centuries people of many different nations and cultures have looked up to the skies and perceived patterns, objects, mythical creatures from scattered stars.

This work, initially titled 'Chaos', began as a study for my project 'Gestalt' to explore the idea of working with a foundation of hidden random points and connecting points with curves in interesting ways. Almost by accident I discovered a technique which ended up creating outputs resembling scenes from some otherworldly cosmos. While it produced some visually interesting outputs, they didn't quite fit the direction for 'Gestalt' and only a portion of the algorithm was used. 

The study was recently revisited and further refined to explore something different to 'Gestalt' (yet would nod to it), blur the lines between abstraction and figuration, and lean into the atmospheric moodiness of that once accidental output. 'Constellations' plays with the concept of interconnectivity, the meeting and interacting of hidden elements, and the emergence of patterns and interpretations from chance encounters (or kismet).

---

Released for VerticalCrypto Art invites | LONDON 2022.

---

Controls:
• 'R' reassembles the piece
• 'B' toggles the frame

Note: Some mints may take time to fully render in live mode.

Made in p5js
Created Oct 2022
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: CELDAS #289
metadata.description:
Cells, called "CELDAS" in Spanish, are spaces separated by lines or stripes in a geometric structure. Generally, cells are formed when the stripes intersect to form a mesh or grid. Each cell formed by these stripes can be filled with a color to create a design.
I love the way I can play with the horizontality and verticality of the stripes to create unique and original geometric patterns, and how through different sizes of stripes an infinity of pieces are formed ranging from the minimalist and sophisticated to the most colorful and expressive, bringing each piece a fresh and current air within a vibrant color palette.
The DNA of this collection is my passion for stripes and colors, both united in a single project that reflects my love in each piece.
I hope you enjoy it as much as I do!

metadata.name: THE END #119
metadata.description:
An ode to our short lives & our even shorter years, a lingering feeling of it having escaped through our grasp as we were just about to comprehend its meanings, shoved into another cycle of life and death. Unlike our cosmos both above and below, the universe and the microscopic world - omnipresent and continuous; time almost feels like a prison on land, a boat without a sail in the sea, an astronaut without a spaceship - a binding of our mind and behaviour. As if we were too afraid to face the eternal chain of feedback loop that engulfs us all. So as this year comes to an end and another one begins, here is my last piece.

This year was full of surprises for all of us, packed with floods, fires, hurricanes, wars and amazing new discoveries! This piece was inspired by the constant yearning to escape into the endless space. And as James Web Telescope keeps discovering new stuff out there, it makes me question - is the big bang real? Or has it always been like this? Are we very close to discovering something new? What if just like time, space was just another loop? How do the different dimensions intertwine with each other? Despite all hardships, this year end seems to bring about hope - hope for a better exciting future. Hope that we might survive our doomsday. Hope that we might actually be ready to face the endless void beyond earthly time and space. 

And with that said I hereby introduce my last piece for 2022, the cosmic fidget spinner with melancholic 90s generative audio! 

Interactivity: 

Press M for the audio (Proceed with caution I am not really a musician)
Press P to check performance 
Press S to save a 1920x1920 screenshot 
Click and drag over the artwork to play around with the cosmic sculpture 

In case you are on the phone, you can use the invisible menu button at the top right corner of the frame for accessing all of the above functionality!    

And best of luck for 2023!

Jaalibandar '22

metadata.description:
Abstract structures floating in space.

Levitation continues my exploration of Suprematism and Geometric Abstraction. It contains my developments and ideas for the past half a year.
Starting as mostly inspired by Kleine Welten (Small Worlds) series by Wassily Kandinsky, the collection evolved more into Suprematic compositions.
